ast Riding, England, United Kingdom","Lamely, Norwell, Nottinghamshire, England":"Norwell, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Otteby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom","Eaton Socon, Bedfordshire, England":"Eaton Socon, Bedfordshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Willerby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from Willerby (ER Yorks)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Robert de Willerby was born in 1335, in Willerby, Yorkshire East Riding, England, United Kingdom as the son of Robert de Willerby. He married Isabella Otteby in 1356, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 daughters. He died on 9 May 1421, in Lincolnshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 86."},"et":{"1335–9 May 1421":"1335–9. mai 1421","1335–1421":"1335–1421","1339–1421":"1339–1421","1371–1421":"1371–1421","1380–1430":"1380–1430","1299–1340":"1299–1340","1335":"1335","1356":"1356","1421":"1421","1299":"1299","9 May 1421":"9. mai 1421","1430":"1430","1340":"1340","1371":"1371","1380":"1380","about 1340":"umbes 1340","1339":"1339","Willerby, Yorkshire, England":"Willerby, Yorkshire East Riding, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lamely, Norwell, Nottinghamshire, England":"Norwell, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Otteby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Eaton Socon, Bedfordshire, England":"Eaton Socon, Bedfordshire, England"},"fi":{"1335–9 May 1421":"1335–9. toukokuuta 1421","1335–1421":"1335–1421","1339–1421":"1339–1421","1371–1421":"1371–1421","1380–1430":"1380–1430","1299–1340":"1299–1340","1335":"1335","1356":"1356","1421":"1421","1299":"1299","9 May 1421":"9. toukokuuta 1421","1430":"1430","1340":"1340","1371":"1371","1380":"1380","about 1340":"noin 1340","1339":"1339","Willerby, Yorkshire, England":"Willerby, Yorkshire East Riding, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Lamely, Norwell, Nottinghamshire, England":"Norwell, Nottinghamshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Otteby, Lincolnshire, England":"Lincolnshire, Englanti, Yh